@ENDNODE



@NODE MN_NEW "Menu Project/New"

        @{b}New@{ub}

@{i}New@{ui} allows the user to reset to the default Mandelbrot coordinates.
@ENDNODE



@NODE MN_OPEN "Menu Project/Open »"

        @{b}Open »@{ub}

@{i}Open@{ui} lets you open either the coordinates or the colors made by Mandela or some other programs.

Open  »
	@{"Coordinates.." link MN_OP_COORDINATES}
	@{"Colors..     " link MN_OP_COLORS}
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_OP_COORDINATES "Menu Project/Open/Coordinates.."

        @{b}Open coordinates..@{ub}

@{i}Open coordinates@{ui} loads coordinates from an IFF ILBM file with a MAND or MANC chunk. I don't know of any Amigan Mandelbrot program that can save images and don't do it in one of these formats. If the IFF ILBM file contains a CMAP chunk and you have defined you want to @{"load colors with images" link MN_LOADCOLORSWITHIMAGES}, the color palette of the picture will be loaded. Also some options set at the @{"Edit colors" link MN_EDITCOLORS} window will affect loading of colors.

Mandela can also @{"save coordinates" link MN_SA_COORDINATES}.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_OP_COLORS "Menu Project/Open/Colors.."

        @{b}Load colors..@{ub}

@{i}Open colors@{ui} loads the colors from an IFF ILBM file with a CMAP chunk. Virtually all of Amiga's graphical software can create such files.

Some options set at the @{"Edit colors" link MN_EDITCOLORS} window will affect loading of colors.

Mandela can also @{"save colors" link MN_SA_COLORS}, and it does so also if you ask it to @{"save coordinates" link MN_SA_COORDINATES}.
@ENDNODE




@NODE MN_SAVE "Menu Project/Save »"

        @{b}Save »@{ub}

@{i}Save@{ui} lets you save some properties of your projects.

		@{"Image..      " link MN_SA_IMAGE}
		@{"Coordinates.." link MN_SA_COORDINATES}
		@{"Colors..     " link MN_SA_COLORS}
		@{"Prefs        " link MN_SA_PREFS}
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_SA_IMAGE "Menu Project/Save/Image.."

        @{b}Save image@{ub}

@{i}Save image@{ui} will save the current screen to an IFF ILBM file.

Also special Mandelbrot chunks called MANC and MAND are saved. Thus images saved with Mandela can be loaded to virtually any other Mandelbrot programs on Amiga.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_SA_COORDINATES "Menu Project/Save/Coordinates.."

        @{b}Save coordinates@{ub}

@{i}Save coordinates@{ui} saves the coordinates and colormap of the current Mandelbrot rendering as an IFF ILBM file.

The colors are saved as a 256-color CMAP chunk, and the coordinates are saved to both MANC and MAND chunks. Virtually every Amigan graphical software can read this format. The @{"coordinates" link MN_OP_COORDINATES} can later be reloaded by Mandela or virtually any other Amigan Mandelbrot calculating program.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MN_SA_COLORS "Menu Project/Save/Colors.."

        @{b}Save colors@{ub}

@{i}Save colors@{ui} will save the colors of the current Mandelbrot rendering as an IFF ILBM file.

The colors are saved as a 256-color CMAP chunk. Virtually every Amigan graphical software can read this format. The @{"colors" link MN_OP_COLORS} can later be reloaded by Mandela.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_SA_PREFS "Menu Project/Save/Prefs"

        @{b}Save prefs@{ub}

@{i}Save prefs@{ui} will save your current Mandela @{"calculation" link MN_CALCULATION} and @{"preferences" link MN_PREFS} settings as the default values. Next time you start Mandela, these settings will be in use.
@ENDNODE



@NODE MN_INFO "Menu Project/Info"

        @{b}Info@{ub}

@{i}Info@{ui} will give you some basic information of Mandela.
@ENDNODE



@NODE MN_QUIT "Menu Project/Quit"

        @{b}Quit@{ub}

Can you ever guess what this is for? If not, tough luck.
@ENDNODE



@NODE MN_CALCULATION "Menu Calculation"

        @{b}Calculation@{ub}

@{i}Calculation@{ui} gives you control over the Mandelbrot image calculation.

Calculation»
	@{"Precision       »" link MN_PRECISION}
	@{"Max.Iterations  »" link MN_MAXITERATIONS}
	@{"Threshold       »" link MN_THRESHOLD}
	@{"Coordinates..    " link MN_COORDINATES}
	@{"Recalculate      " link MN_RECALCULATE}
@ENDNODE



@NODE MN_PRECISION "Menu Calculation/Precision »"

	@{b}Precision »@{ub}

@{i}Precision@{ui} lets you define one of four calculation precisions depending on your needs. The better the precision, the deeper you can @{"zoom in" link MANDELA_BASE}, and the slower Mandela runs (this is not the case on all Amiga models, see below).

The selections you can make are:

@{b}Int 16@{ub}
This precision uses 16-bit integer fixed point arithmetic to do the @{"Mandelbrot" link MANDELBROT} calculations. This is by far the fastest way to do calculation on basic Amiga model with a CPU with a 16-bit multiplication command (68000 and 68010).

@{b}Int 32@{ub}
This precision uses 32-bit integer fixed point arithmetic to do the Mandelbrot calculations. The fully 32-bit processors (68020, 68030 and 68040) can multiply 32-bit integers without problems, but on the older processors every 32-bit multiplication must be emulated with from 2 to 3 16-bit multiplications. Thus, Int 32 is almost as fast than Int 16 on 32-bit processors, but somewhat slower on 16-bit processors.

@{b}Float 64@{ub}
This precision uses IEEE double precision floating point arithmetic to do the Mandelbrot calculations. If a math coprocessor is available (68881 or 68882), this will be a reasonably fast mode; about half the speed of Int 16. The internal FPU in the 68040 makes this mode very fast: about @{i}as@{ui} fast as Int 16. However, if you don't have a math coprocessor, Mandela will use the OS routines to emulate the math coprocessor, and that is r_e_a_l_l_y s_l_o_w. As a matter of fact, so slow that you usually don't want to use this mode at all.

@{b}Weird 32@{ub}
While developing the Int 32 -calculation routines I made a range check programming error. However, I liked the result so here it is as a separate precision selection. The speed it comparable to Int 32.

@{b}Auto@{ub}
If you don't want to mind yourself about setting the right precision, you may ask Mandela to automatically set the right precision for you. It will do so every time you zoom or load an image. Selecting this precision mode will exclude all other precision selections.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_MAXITERATIONS "Menu Calculation/Max.Iterations »"

	@{b}Max.Iterations »@{ub}

@{i}Max.Iterations@{ui} lets you select the maximum number of iterations Mandela may do for one @{"Mandelbrot" link MANDELBROT} calculation point. The higher the value is the slower Mandela will run in deep areas and the better the image quality will be.

The selections you can make are:
30 62 126 254 510 1022 2046 4094 8190 16382 32766 65534

If you choose an iteration value larger than 254, you that the whole image will have to be recalculated. If you haven't switched the @{"warning off" link MN_OKPROMPTS}, you still may cancel your menu selection.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_THRESHOLD "Menu Calculation/Threshold »"

	@{b}Threshold »@{ub}

Normally you get one color for each @{"Mandelbrot" link MANDELBROT} @{"iteration" link MN_MAXITERATIONS}. However, with very deep objects, you may want to have the color changing only for every other, or fourth iteration count. This may be achieved by selecting one value from the @{i}Threshold@{ui} menu.

If you are running Mandela with a @{"non-HAM screen" link MN_SCREENMODE} and without any @{"dithering" link MN_DITHER}, Mandela will just show the same colour for n steps. Otherwise, the colors between your actual @{"palette" link MN_EDITCOLORS} colors will be represented as accurately as possible.

The selections you can make are:
1 2 4 8 16 32 64 128

The screen will be updated immediately to reflect the new threshold value. If the calculation was not finished when you chose this menu selection, it will resume only after the display has been updated.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_COORDINATES "Menu Calculation/Coordinates.."

	@{b}Coordinates@{ub}

@{i}Coordinates@{ui} will let you set numerical coordinates for the @{"Mandelbrot" link MANDELBROT} complex area.

You will be presented with a requester with three lines that have the values of the current coordinates and that you can set. The values are:
Minimum Real component, Maximum Real component and Center of Imaginary component. The following rules define the values of the components:

-2.2 <= MIN_REAL < MAX_REAL <= 1.3
-1.4 <= CENT_IMAG <= 1.4

The way of defining these values is somewhat different to most other Mandelbrot programs, where you define lower and upper limits also for the Imaginary component. I have chosen this approach, because Mandela keeps the aspect ratio of the image always automatically correct, and defining all the four limits would break this.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_RECALCULATE "Menu Calculation/Recalculate"

	@{b}Recalculate@{ub}

Sometimes you may want to @{i}recalculate@{ui} your already calculated image. This may happen if you, for instance, have changed the @{"precision" link MN_PRECISION} or @{"maximum iterations" link MN_MAXITERATIONS}.
@ENDNODE





@NODE MN_PREFS "Menu Prefs »"

	@{b}Prefs@{ub}

@{i}Prefs@{ui} lets you set the basic settings you want to use. You may also @{"save your preferences" link MN_SA_PREFS} (also all @{"calculation settings" link MN_CALCULATION} will be saved).

@{"Prefs      »" link MN_PREFS}
	@{"Screen mode..           " link MN_SCREENMODE}
	@{"Edit colors..           " link MN_EDITCOLORS}
	@{"User priority          »" link MN_USERPRIORITY}
	@{"Calc priority          »" link MN_CALCPRIORITY}
	@{"OK prompts             »" link MN_OKPROMPTS}
	@{"Beep after calc.       »" link MN_BEEPAFTERCALC}
	@{"Reject modes           »" link MN_REJECTMODES}
	@{"Color scrolling        »" link MN_COLORSCROLLING}
	@{"Save mode              »" link MN_SAVEMODE}
	@{"Dithering              »" link MN_DITHER}
	@{"Continuous update      ×" link MN_CONTINUOUSDRAW}
	@{"Load colors w/ images  ×" link MN_LOADCOLORSWITHIMAGES}
	@{"Show title bar         ×" link MN_SHOWTITLEBAR}
	@{"Show info window       ×" link MN_SHOWINFOWINDOW}
	@{"Info window follows    ×" link MN_INFOWINDOWFOLLOWS}
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_SCREENMODE "Menu Prefs/Screen mode.."

	@{b}Screen mode..@{ub}

This selection lets you use the @{i}screen mode@{ui} and display size you want Mandela to use. There are several considerations you should make in selecting your screen mode:

The screen mode requester only works with OS 2.1 and later. If you are running OS 2.0x, you must update your asl.library to v38 to be able to use this feature of Mandela. And, of couse, Mandela will not be very usable without a screen mode selector.

To make quick tests take a screen mode with little resolution and render your final versions in higher resolution.

Mandela can make use of Amiga's @{"HAM6" link HAM} display mode to emulate 256 colors from a 4096 color palette. This will be by far the best colormode for older Amigas with the old graphic chips. It is somewhat slower to draw in HAM compared to other modes, but the result is usually worth the little wait. On new AGA-equipped Amigas where you can access 256 color modes out of a 16.8 million color palette, it is recommended that you @{"disable" link MN_REJECTMODES} HAM modes alltogether.

If you @{i}do@{ui} select a HAM mode on an AGA-Amiga, you may select HAM8 (16.8 million colors). This is, however, not a valid selection, and you will be forced to HAM6 (4096) colors by Mandela.

You may select a screen that is larger than your actual display area. This way you may create very big and attractive images. You may scroll the display by moving the mouse to where you want to go.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_EDITCOLORS "Menu Prefs/Edit colors.."

	@{b}Edit colors..@{ub}

@{i}Edit colors@{ui} will let you edit your default colormap. You will be presented with a window, which's crude Ascii representation is below:

+-+--------------------------------+
|·|Edit colors                     |
+-+--------------------------------+
| ,______________________________. |
|R|                              | |
| `------------------------------´ |
| ,______________________________. |
|G|                              | |
| `------------------------------´ |
| ,______________________________. |
|B|                              | |
| `------------------------------´ |
| XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX |
| Load ¤Interpolate         Save   |
|      ¤Skip 4 first colors        |
| Use   (Sinus editor)      Cancel |
+----------------------------------+

You will see the current 252 color colormap at the line marked with X's. If you have less than 256 colors in your current @{"screen mode" link MN_SCREENMODE}, you will get the same approximation of the colormap Mandela uses in the image calculation. You may edit the colors by changing their Red, Green and Blue components at the @{i}R@{ui}, @{i}G@{ui} and @{i}B@{ui} subwindows. The better the vertical resolution of your @{"screen mode" link MN_SCREENMODE} is, the more precisely you can edit the colormap. This will usually only have effect in Amigas with the AGA graphic chips.

The options are as follows:

@{i}Load@{ui} is similar to the menu selection @{"Open colors" link MN_OP_COLORS}.

@{i}Save@{ui} is similar to the menu selection @{"Save colors" link MN_SA_COLORS}.

@{i}Interpolate@{ui} affects the way Load and Save works. Mandela uses a 252 color colormap, and if the colormap to be loaded has less than that amount of colors, Mandela will widen the colormap to fully cover its 252 color colormap. If @{i}Interpolate@{ui} is off and a smaller colormap is loaded, only the first colors are changed.

@{i}Skip 4 first colors@{ui} tells Mandela to skip the 4 first colors when loading a colormap. Many programs, including Mandela, use the first 2 or 4 colours to screen borders, and only the rest of the colors will be actual image data. Loading these 4 first colors will usually result in poorer quality than skipping them. This option is automatically set, if the colormap to be loaded has 256 colors or more.

@{i}(Sinus editor)@{ui} is not usable yet.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_USERPRIORITY "Menu Prefs/User priority »"

	@{b}User priority »@{ub}

@{i}User priority@{ui} lets you select the priority in which Mandela's user interface is run. You may either select @{i}Inherited@{ui}, or you may select one of the values 5 4 3 2 1 0 -1 -2 -5 -10.

If you use InheritedPri, Mandela will use the same priority that its starter process had (usually 0). The @{"calculation process" link MANDELA_BASE} will get a priority that is 1 less than the UI priority.

If you select a spesific value, Mandela's UI will run at that priority. You may not select a lower value to the UI than you have @{"chosen" link MN_CALCPRIORITY} for the @{"calculation process" link MANDELA_BASE}. This will usually make some priority values inactive.

In Amiga priorities a higher value is better and 0 is the default. My recommendation for the UI priority is 1. That way the UI will be smooth and it will respond quickly to your actions.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_CALCPRIORITY "Menu Prefs/Calc priority »"

	@{b}Calc priority »@{ub}

@{i}Calc priority@{ui} lets you select the priority in which Mandela's calculation process is run. You may select one of the values 4 3 2 1 0 -1 -2 -3 -6 -11.

If you are using the @{"inherited priority" link MN_USERPRIORITY} for your @{"user interface" link MANDELA_BASE}, the calculation process priority can't be selected.

When you have selected a value, Mandela's calculation process will run at that priority. You may not select a higher value to the calculation process than you have @{"chosen" link MN_USERPRIORITY} for the @{"UI" link MANDELA_BASE}.

In Amiga priorities a higher value is better and 0 is the default. My recommendation for the calculation process priority is -1. That way it will not affect interactive tasks and while calculating a slow image you can forget the whole existence of Mandela.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_OKPROMPTS "Menu Prefs/OK prompts »"

	@{b}OK prompts »@{ub}

There are several occasions where Mandela wants to ask the user if it's OK to do something or not, or it just wants to give you a message. From experience I knowthat all the people do @{u}not@{uu} want to see some messages over and over again, while other like the feel of safety they get with them. Thus, the following messages can be turned on and off:

@{b}Mouse zoom@{ub}
If you @{"zoom with the mouse" link MANDELA_BASE}, you will be asked if you really wanted to do that. I strongly recommend you keep this selection on.

@{b}Previous zoom@{ub}
If you select @{"previous zoom" link MN_PREVIOUS}, you will be asked if you really wanted to do that.

@{b}Other zooms@{ub}
If you select any of the @{"other zooms" link MN_OTHERZOOMS}, you will be asked if you really wanted to do that.

@{b}Calc-buf.warn@{ub}
If you select more than 254 @{"iterations" link MN_MAXITERATIONS}, and you haven't used that many iterations before in that screen mode on that session, you will be asked, if you want to do a whole recalculation. Why this is done, can be read in @{"The basics of Mandela" MANDELA_BASE}.

@{b}HAM8 warn@{ub}
Mandela can't @{"select" link MN_SCREENMODE} the 16.8 million color HAM8 mode of the new AGA Amigas. If you still insist on selecting it, Mandela will default to 4096 color HAM6 to emulate its 256 internal colors. If this warning is set, you will be noticed of the defaulting.

@{b}Recalculation@{ub}
If you select @{"Recalculation" link MN_RECALCULATE}, you will be asked if you really wanted to do that.

@{b}New@{ub}
If you select the @{"New" link MN_NEW}, you will be asked if you really wanted to do that.

@{b}Quit@{ub}
If you select the @{"Quit" link MN_QUIT}, you will be asked if you really wanted to do that.
@ENDNODE




@NODE MN_BEEPAFTERCALC "Menu Prefs/Beep after calc. »"

	@{b}Beep after calc. »@{ub}

Calculating Mandelbrot images can take quite a while. With this option you can make Mandela notify by flashing every screen and beeping when it has finished calculating an image. There are three options you can select:

@{b}Always@{ub}
Beep always when calculation is finished.

@{b}If calc >1min@{ub}
Beep if calculation has taken at least one minute.

@{b}Never@{ub}
Never beep.
@ENDNODE



@NODE MN_REJECTMODES "Menu Prefs/Reject modes »"

	@{b}Reject modes »@{ub}

@{i}Reject modes@{ui} allows you to reject certain screen modes you never want to see in your @{"Screen Mode Requester" link MN_SCREENMODE}. The available selections are:

@{b}Width < 320@{ub}: screen modes where display width is ridiculously low
@{b}HAM@{ub}        : HAM modes. Recommended if you have AGA graphic chips
@{b}All but HAM@{ub}: all modes that do not use HAM
@{b}NTSC@{ub}       : NTSC modes (that are compatible with N-American TV)
@{b}PAL@{ub}        : PAL modes (that are compatible with European TV)
@{b}DBLNTSC@{ub}    : doublescanned NTSC modes
@{b}DBLPAL@{ub}     : doublescanned PAL modes
@{b}Multiscan@{ub}  : VGA-compatible multiscan modes
@{b}Euro 36@{ub}    : euro 36 Hz modes
@{b}Euro 72@{ub}    : euro 72 Hz modes
@{b}Super 72@{ub}   : super 72 Hz modes
@{b}A2024@{ub}      : Amiga A2024 monochrome monitor
@ENDNODE



@NODE MN_COLORSCROLLING "Menu Prefs/Color scrolling »"

	@{b}Color scrolling »@{ub}

@{i}Color scrolling@{ui} lets the user control color scrolling in a Mandelbrot image. This menu is not available if you are running Mandela on an Amiga with an OS older than 3.0, if the @{"screen mode" link MN_SCREENMODE} is a @{"HAM" link HAM} mode, or if you have less than 8 colors.

The following color scroll selections are available:

@{b}Stop   @{ub} Stops color scrolling and leaves the palette as it is
@{b}Forward@{ub} Starts color scrolling in forward direction
@{b}Reverse@{ub} Starts color scrolling in reverse direction
@{b}Faster @{ub} Makes colors scroll faster
@{b}Slower @{ub} Makes colors scroll slower
@{b}Reset  @{ub} Stops color scrolling and restores the palette
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_SAVEMODE "Menu Prefs/Save mode »"

	@{b}Save mode »@{ub}

@{i}Save mode@{ui} lets the user control how @{"image saving" link MN_SA_IMAGE} is performed.

The following selections are available:

@{b}Screen    @{ub} Everything is saved including headers + info window
@{b}Mandelbrot@{ub} Only the actual Mandelbrot image is saved
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_DITHER "Menu Prefs/Dithering »"

	@{b}Dithering »@{ub}

@{i}Dithering@{ui} lets the user control how images are displayed.

The following selections are available:

@{b}None@{ub} No dithering
@{b}Low @{ub} Some dithering
@{b}High@{ub} Accurate dithering

Using dithering makes screen updates somewhat slower.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_CONTINUOUSDRAW "Menu Prefs/Continuous update  ×"

	@{b}Continuous update  ×@{ub}

This switch will select if you want to see all the time Mandela updating its screen when it's calculating an image.

If you clear this selection Mandela will only update your display after it has finished a whole scanline. This may be considerably faster especially with quickly calculated pictures and lots of DMA activity going on.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_LOADCOLORSWITHIMAGES "Menu Prefs/Load colors w/ images  ×"

	@{b}Load colors w/ images  ×@{ub}

This switch lets you select if you want to load a colormap with @{"coordinates" link MN_OP_COORDINATES}.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_SHOWTITLEBAR "Show title bar  ×"

	@{b}Show title bar  ×@{ub}

This switch defines if you want the upper screen border to be shown on Mandela's screen.
@ENDNODE



@NODE MN_SHOWINFOWINDOW "Show info window  ×"

	@{b}Show info window  ×@{ub}

This switch defines if you want to see an information window that gives you calculation time estimates and other information.

If this window is in your way, you may temporarily drag it to another location. It will, however, come back to its original place when it is updated for the next time.

If you are using a screen larger than your display, you may want to define if the info window is to @{"follow" link MN_INFOWINDOWFOLLOWS} you when you scroll around the virtual screen.

If you are using OS 3.0 or newer, the menus of Mandela are also attached to this window. That way it Mandela's menus work even if you activate the information window.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MN_INFOWINDOWFOLLOWS "Info window follows  ×"

	@{b}Info window follows  ×@{ub}

This switch defines if you want to have your @{"information window" link MN_SHOWINFOWINDOW} to follow you if you are using a big autoscrolling @{"screen" link MN_SCREENMODE}.
@ENDNODE




@NODE MN_ZOOM "Menu Zoom"

        @{b}Zoom@{ub}

Zoom       »
	@{"In  2X  " link MN_OTHERZOOMS}
	@{"In  5X  " link MN_OTHERZOOMS}
	@{"In 10X  " link MN_OTHERZOOMS}
	@{"Out  2X " link MN_OTHERZOOMS}
	@{"Out  5X " link MN_OTHERZOOMS}
	@{"Out 10X " link MN_OTHERZOOMS}
	@{"Previous" link MN_PREVIOUS}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MN_OTHERZOOMS "Menu Zoom/(in and out zooms)"

	@{b}Other zooms@{ub}

The @{i}In 2X@{ui}, @{i}5X@{ui} and @{i}10X@{ui} zooms you in the specified amount. Usually you don't have much use for there.

The @{i}Out 2X@{ui}, @{i}5X@{ui} and @{i}10X@{ui} zooms you out the specified amount. These can be used if you feel you are a bit too deep and you can´t go back with the @{"Zoom previous" link MN_PREVIOUS} menu selection.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MN_PREVIOUS "Menu Zoom/Previous"

	@{b}Previous@{ub}

This will let you zoom back to the previous position you were in. A 20 zoom history (that is not saved with the @{"preferences" link MN_SA_PREFS} or the @{"coordinates" link MN_SA_COORDINATES}) is maintained. There is no way to redo an undoed zoom stage.
@ENDNODE


@NODE MANDELBROT "The basics of a Mandelbrot image"

	@{b}The basics of a Mandelbrot image@{ub}, or Z=Z˛+C

Great thanks to Benoit Mandelbrot, who invented this simple formula in 1985. Chaos theory is fun :-)

You know complex numbers? Not? Too bad, because I am not going to explain them here in detail. There are other sources for that. To make it short, complex numbers are 2-dimensional numbers in a way that they have a Real part, and an Imaginary part, whereas the real numbers we use every day only have Real parts.

Now, think of real number values as 2-dimensional coordinates, where the Real part is on the x-axis and the Imaginary part is on the y-axis. This way every point in a 2-dimensional coordinate space has a unique complex value.

Now, to draw a Mandelbrot image we'll do the following iterative operation in pseudo-code for every single point (C is the pixel to be calculated):

@{b}INTEGER FUNCTION@{ub} CALCULATE_POINT(@{b}COMPLEX@{ub} C)
	@{b}COMPLEX@{ub} Z = (0.0, 0.0)
	@{b}INTEGER@{ub} COUNTER = 0

	@{b}WHILE@{ub} (@{b}ABS@{ub}(Z) < 2.0) @{b}BEGIN@{ub}	@{i}# always true for the first test@{ui}
		Z = Z˛ + C
		COUNTER = COUNTER + 1
	@{b}END WHILE@{ub}

	@{b}RETURN COUNTER@{ub}
@{b}END FUNCTION@{ub}

It has been proven (exercise: how?) that if the absolute value of a point exceeds 2.0, it will continue to grow very quickly to explode the limits out of every limit. That also causes the fact that it isn't reasonable to calculate Mandelbrot points for coordinates that has a Real or Imaginary componen that have an absolute value greater than 2.0.

Thus, when the magic limit 2.0 is reached, the iterations stop for that point and the value of COUNTER will determine the color of that pixel. It's that simple!

Although the formula for calculating Mandelbrot images looks deceivingly simple, the image drawn is full of complex patterns. And, it can be @{"zoomed" link MOUSE_ZOOM} infinitely (see @{i}caveats@{ui} below), and you'll never find precisely the same patterns twice. The exception to this is that the whole Mandelbrot image is mirrored around their x-axis.


	@{b}Caveats@{ub}

Some of the coordinates in the Mandelbrot set are of the kind where the absolute value @{i}never@{ui} grows over the magic limit 2.0. Because a program calculating Mandelbrot points would stop forever calculating such a point, an @{"iteration limit" link MN_MAXITERATIONS} must be provided. The pixels that never got a good iteration value are usually colored black. A higher amount of iterations help reduce the black areas somewhat and, naturally, also makes the calculation slower.

Although the Mandelbrot image can theoretically be zoomed infinitely, there are always limits on the precision that a computer can calculate with. That sets a limit to the amount a user can zoom his images. Because integer calculation is usually much faster than floating point calculation, many Mandelbrot programs offer a possibility to calculate images with fixed-point arithmetic simulated with integers. Usually, though, the @{"precision" link MN_PRECISION} of integers are less than floating point numbers.

The colors used to represent the final image are naturally not set. Many images can be greatly enhanced by giving them exciting @{"colormaps" link MN_EDITCOLORS}. Also the fact that the color change for every different iteration value, is not enforced nor always desirable. Some programs give the user a definable @{"threshold" link MN_THRESHOLD} that lets the user define how many iterations are needed to change the color.

Although, principally, every point in a Mandelbrot image should be calculated to display an image, there are some @{"optimizations" link MANDELBROT_OPT} that allows programs to get (almost) the exactly correct result with a smaller computational price.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MANDELBROT_OPT "Optimizations in calculating a Mandelbrot image"

	@{b}Optimizations@{ub}


The earliest Mandelbrot programs simply calculated every single point in a Mandelbrot image. This was very slow especially if the image contained large @{"black" link MANDELBROT} areas.


The first program to use optimizations that @{"I" link AUTHOR} saw, was @{i}TurboMandel@{ui} made in the late 1980's by Philip Marivoet and Nico François.

TurboMandel used a "divide-and-conquer" -method to spare calculations. The idea was to divide the screen in 4 rectangles and calculate all the pixels on the sides of the rectangles. If @{i}all@{ui} of them were of the same color (or, rather, same amount of iterations), the whole rectangle could be painted with that color without calculating the inner pixels of it. If there were pixels of other colors, the rectangle was (recursively) divided into 4 smaller rectangles and the cycle was redone.

This method caused the calculation speed of the black areas to get very much faster.


Later in 1990, Nico François' MandelBlitz used a different approach called contour crawling: it followed the outlines of areas and painted them without calculating any inner pixels at all. This is a bit hard to explain, but since Mandela uses the same algorithm, it is easy for you to check this out.
@ENDNODE



